FontName: ChessCancunC2
FullName: ChessCancunC2 Regular
FamilyName: ChessCancunC2
Weight: Regular
Copyright: This work is public domain.\n\nIn more detail: This work is derived from ChessMerida, which is a font\nreleased in the late 1990s under a "freeware" license:\n\n>The font is freeware, I hope it is useful for the chess buddies. If you\n>want to repay us, you can send us some other fonts for creating chess\n>diagrams (we are collecting them).\n\nHowever, as per US copyright law, only the vector instructions for the\nfont can be copyrighted.  The forms of the chess figurines are not subject\nto copyright.  As per [the law Stack\nExchange](https://archive.ph/20260208233651/https://law.stackexchange.com/questions/52559/can-i-use-chess-diagrams-in-my-book-without-infringing-any-copyrights-having-to)\n\n>if the diagrams were represented using bitmaps [...] that would merely\n>be a representation of the appearance and not include Marroquin's\n>creative work\n\nHence, this repo does not include any copied vector representations,\nneither those made by Marroquin nor by the book he got the visual\nimages from.  All SVG and other vector representations are derived\nfrom the raster images in the PNG directory.  The TTF font here looks\nlike Chess Merida, but at the vector level, it's quite different (it\ngenerally uses a lot more vectors to make the same images).\n\nIn addition, it is my understanding that Marroquin does not feel he\nrequires any compensation for this font, since he talks about it being\nfree to use; any donations are optional.  Indeed, if I could locate\nMarroquin, I would give him a donation.\n\nBecause of this, all files here are public domain, free of any and all\ncopyright restrictions.\n\nSince [the font is over 25 years\nold](https://archive.ph/19991128171035/http://www.enpassant.dk/chess/fontimg/merida.htm),\nany design patents or other IP protecting the appearance of this font\nin many jurisdictions has expired.\n\nIn addition, further web searching has found [a book from 1952 with\na font substantially like this\nfont](https://archive.ph/20260212011847/https://chess.stackexchange.com/questions/14979/what-is-the-origin-of-the-merida-chess-font).\n
